div.h2: Welcome to Hamilton Township School District

strong.style: font-family: Arial; text-align: center; color: rgb(34, 34, 34);

br.span: Only sign in once per day!

span.style: font-size: 10pt; text-align: left; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: rgb(34, 34, 34);

p.span: The President of the United States, by the authority vested in him by the Constitution and the laws of the United States of America, including sections 201 and 301 of the National Emergencies Act (50 U.S.C. 1601 et seq.) and consistent with section 1135 of the Social Security Act (SSA), as amended (42 U.S.C. 1320b-5), has heretofore proclaimed that the COVID-19 outbreak in the United States constitutes a national emergency, beginning March 1, 2020. Pursuant to this declaration, and given the recent attention to the potential impacts of coronavirus (COVID-19), and as a general precaution to remind local governmental units of options available to ensure the continued regular operation of local government [Executive Order 103 (Murphy 3/9/2020) and Executive Order 107 (Murphy 3/20/2020)], and the mechanisms that have been used by local governments during emergencies that render in-person meetings less than optimal, pursuant to the provisions of N.J.S.A. 40:55D-11 and 12, a public hearing and board meeting which is the subject of this notice has been scheduled for April 27, 2020 at 7:00 p.m. The public hearing and board meeting will be held telephonically and online only.

span.style: font-size: 10pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: rgb(34, 34, 34);

p.span: If you do not have computer access, you may contact Anne-Marie Fala, Business Administrator/ Board Secretary, Hamilton Township School District via telephone - - 609-476-6290.

p.span: The Hamilton Township School District’s Food Services Department will make every attempt to provide meals for all students enrolled in our district during this crisis.

p.span: William Davies Middle School is a pick up process through the main entrance drive through. When you arrive, leave your windows up and remain in your car until instructed to pull up. And most importantly, please remember social distancing.

div.p: The Peanut butter and jelly sandwich may be frozen and can be kept frozen for up to one month. Simply refrigerate the sandwich to defrost. If you plan on eating the sandwich within an hour, you may defrost on the counter at room temperature. Fresh fruit such as apples and oranges should be refrigerated. Breakfast items such as dried craisins and raisins do not require refrigeration.
